Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Minimal scanner state for a stream-based lexer: just enough to know where
we are (position, line, column), what we're looking at (current_char),
and the bounds (length) of the source buffer. No layout stack is needed
because TypeScript is brace-based, not indentation-sensitive like
Haskell/Python.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
6 x i64 record (48 bytes). offsets: 0 = source string handle, 8 = byte
position, 16 = source length cache, 24 = current_char (0 marks EOF in
this scanner), 32 = 1-based line, 40 = 1-based column. Layout matches
create_lexer's 48-byte allocation exactly.
@End Implementation

Type called "TypeScriptLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code string
    position as Integer        Note: Current position in source
    length as Integer          Note: Length of source
    current_char as Integer    Note: Current character
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Tokens carry the discriminant plus source span info; lexeme is a
substring handle pointing into the source buffer so we don't copy bytes
on the hot path. This is the universal token shape consumed by the
TypeScript parser stage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
4 x i64 record (32 bytes). offsets: 0 = type constant (TOKEN_* above),
8 = lexeme string handle (may be a freshly-allocated substring), 16 =
1-based line, 24 = 1-based column. Layout matches create_token's 32-byte
allocation exactly.
@End Implementation

Type called "Token":
    type as Integer      Note: Token type constant
    lexeme as Integer    Note: Token text (string pointer)
    line as Integer      Note: Line number
    column as Integer    Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the lexer record and primes the cursor at the first character.
Line and column start at 1 (the conventional 1-based reporting used by
TypeScript tooling). The current_char field is preloaded so the first
call to next_token doesn't need an explicit advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes via Layout. Returns 0 on allocation failure. Writes
source handle (0), position=0 (8), source_length (16), line=1 (32),
column=1 (40), and the first character (24) — read via memory_get_byte
because source is treated as raw bytes here. An empty source leaves
current_char=0 (EOF sentinel).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create TypeScript lexer with source code

    Let lexer_size be 48  Note: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0     Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1    Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 1    Note: column = 1

    Note: Load first character
    If source_length is greater than 0:
        Let first_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, first_char
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 0
    End If

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer record holds no owned heap allocations (the source string is
borrowed), so destruction is a single deallocate of the record itself.
Tokens emitted by the lexer are independently owned by the parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard then Layout.deallocate. Returns 1 unconditionally; callers
that need to detect double-free should track liveness themselves.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy TypeScript lexer

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single-step cursor advance: increments position, reloads current_char,
bumps column. EOF detection sets current_char to 0 so callers can compare
against the same sentinel as the initial empty-source case in
create_lexer. Line tracking is handled by skip_whitespace/skip_comment
when they consume newlines, not here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loads position (8) and length (16), increments position and writes it
back. If past end, writes current_char=0 and returns 0. Otherwise reads
the next byte via memory_get_byte and stores it at offset 24. Bumps
column at offset 40 by 1 — column resets are NOT done here because this
function doesn't see whether the character it stepped over was a newline
(skip_whitespace handles that).
@End Implementation

Process called "advance" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Move to next character and return it

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, next_char

    Note: Update column
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, column plus 1

    Return next_char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-character operators (=== , !== , >>>=, ...) require k-character
lookahead so the scanner can disambiguate before committing. peek is
non-consuming and bounds-safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes peek_pos = position + offset (no negative-offset support;
callers pass 1..3). Returns 0 past EOF (matching current_char's EOF
sentinel); otherwise reads the byte at peek_pos via memory_get_byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Look ahead at character without consuming it

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, peek_pos

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII '0'..'9' predicate used by scan_number. Kept separate from
is_alphanumeric so identifier scanning and numeric scanning can call
into one shared digit definition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Nested range test against ASCII 48..57. Returns 1 only when both
inequalities hold, 0 otherwise. Does not handle hex/oct digits — number
prefix dispatch happens in scan_number.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit (0-9)

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
JavaScript/TypeScript identifier-start predicate. Critically includes
`$` (36) and `_` (95) per ECMAScript spec — both are legal first
characters in identifiers like `$jquery` or `_private`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four explicit cases: ASCII 65..90 (A-Z), 97..122 (a-z), equality with 95
(underscore), and equality with 36 (dollar). Returns 1 on first match,
0 otherwise. Unicode identifier characters are NOT handled by the
bootstrap lexer.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1  Note: A-Z
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1  Note: a-z
        End If
    End If

    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1  Note: underscore
    End If

    If char is equal to 36:
        Return 1  Note: dollar sign (valid in JS/TS identifiers)
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Token lexemes must own their bytes: a token can outlive any transient
view of the source buffer, so the scanner copies the [start, start+len)
window of the source into a fresh owned, null-terminated buffer rather
than aliasing into the source. Bytes are read with memory_get_byte to
match the rest of this lexer, which treats the source handle as a raw
byte buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate len+1 bytes (return 0 on failure or on a non-positive length,
yielding an empty owned string). Copy each source byte at source+start+i
into buffer+i, then write a 0 terminator at offset len. Returns the owned
buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_substring" takes source as Integer, start as Integer, len as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source[start .. start+len) into a fresh owned, null-terminated buffer

    If len is less than 1:
        Let empty be proc allocate from Layout with 1
        If empty is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with empty, 0, 0
        Return empty
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, i, char
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, len, 0

    Return buffer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-continuation predicate. After the first character (handled by
is_alpha), subsequent characters may be digits as well. Composing the two
primitive predicates keeps a single source of truth for both.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha; on match returns 1 immediately. Otherwise returns the
result of is_digit directly (short-circuit OR via early-return).
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let alpha be proc is_alpha with char
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let digit be proc is_digit with char
    Return digit
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Whitespace" here intentionally excludes the line-feed character (10):
skip_whitespace handles LF separately because it also needs to bump the
line counter. Treating LF as whitespace here would lose the line break.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three equality checks: 32 (space), 9 (tab), 13 (CR). Returns 1 on first
match, 0 otherwise. Form-feed and vertical-tab are not recognised even
though ECMAScript allows them — they do not appear in practical TS.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:
        Return 1  Note: space
    End If

    If char is equal to 9:
        Return 1  Note: tab
    End If

    If char is equal to 13:
        Return 1  Note: carriage return
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single allocation point for every token the scanner emits, keeping the
record layout consistent with the Token type and making any future
re-layout a one-place change.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes via Layout; returns 0 on allocation failure. Writes
type at offset 0, lexeme handle at 8, line at 16, column at 24. Lexeme
is borrowed — caller (typically a scan_* function) owns it and is
responsible for ensuring it lives at least as long as the token does.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes type as Integer, lexeme as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create token with given properties

    Let token_size be 32  Note: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
After scan_identifier produces a lexeme, the lexer must decide whether
it is one of TypeScript's ~70 reserved words (matching the spec plus
TypeScript-only keywords like `interface`, `namespace`, `type`,
`readonly`). A flat sequence of equality checks is used rather than a
hash because string_equal is cheap and the cache locality of the linear
form outperforms a hash table at this size.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequential strings_equal calls covering reserved words in alphabetical
order: abstract, any, as, async, await, boolean, ..., yield. Each match
returns its dedicated TOKEN_* constant. Falls through to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
when none match. Returning early on first match keeps the average path
short — common identifiers fall through the whole table only once.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
For pathological inputs (many identifier tokens), this is the hottest
function in the lexer. A perfect-hash dispatch on the first character
would cut comparisons by ~10x; the current implementation is kept linear
for clarity and to avoid a separate codegen step.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a keyword, return token type or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER

    Let is_abstract be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "abstract"
    If is_abstract is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ABSTRACT
    End If

    Let is_any be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "any"
    If is_any is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ANY
    End If

    Let is_as be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "as"
    If is_as is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AS
    End If

    Let is_async be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "async"
    If is_async is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ASYNC
    End If

    Let is_await be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "await"
    If is_await is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AWAIT
    End If

    Let is_boolean be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "boolean"
    If is_boolean is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BOOLEAN
    End If

    Let is_break be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "break"
    If is_break is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_BREAK
    End If

    Let is_case be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "case"
    If is_case is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If

    Let is_catch be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "catch"
    If is_catch is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CATCH
    End If

    Let is_class be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "class"
    If is_class is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CLASS
    End If

    Let is_const be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "const"
    If is_const is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CONST
    End If

    Let is_constructor be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "constructor"
    If is_constructor is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR
    End If

    Let is_continue be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "continue"
    If is_continue is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
    End If

    Let is_debugger be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "debugger"
    If is_debugger is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DEBUGGER
    End If

    Let is_declare be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "declare"
    If is_declare is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DECLARE
    End If

    Let is_default be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "default"
    If is_default is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DEFAULT
    End If

    Let is_delete be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "delete"
    If is_delete is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DELETE
    End If

    Let is_do be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "do"
    If is_do is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    Let is_else be proc string_equals from StringCore with lexeme, "else"
